applications, composites, phase behavior, plasticizer, viscosity and viscoelasticity
1 | INTRODUCTION
The last few years have seen a growing demand for passive vibration and sound control systems in the automobile, railway, aviation, and other industries.1 Composite materials of this type produced today do not always meet the increasing requirements for low mass, durability, high mechanical loss factor, and environmental safety.2 Therefore, researchers in this field of polymer materials
science have to face the challenge of creating formulations and technologies for producing more effective compositions protecting from sound and vibration effects over a broad temperature–frequency range. A literature analysis shows that such materials include butyl rubber (isobutylene–isoprene copolymer, BR), polyisobutylene (PIB), their mixtures, chlorinated BR, BR reclaim, ethylene propylene diene monomer (EPDM) rubber, and polyurethane as polymeric
