imate the effect of thermodynamic affinity of components (BR, plasticizers, and resins of different nature) on certain performance characteristics. Reference 3 analyzed the viscosity and cohesion strength in the compositions with BR, alkyl-phenol-formaldehyde resin, carbon black, and plasticizers of different nature. However, we believe that the conclusion about a better plasticization effect of the aromatic petroleum oil on BR in comparison with paraffin and industrial oils is not correct, taking into account the structure and composition of these plasticizers. Reference 4 discussed a dependence of the physico-mechanical properties and viscosity on the amount of the introduced modifying agents (SP-1045 and 101К alkyl-phenolformaldehyde resins and rosin). The thermodynamic affinity was estimated by the solubility parameter, δ, calculated by Hoy's method,23 to range the studied
modifying agents by their affinity with BR as follows: rosin >101К resin>SP-1045 resin. It was shown that the replacement of the SP-1045 modifying agent, having lower affinity with BR, with rosin, which was closer to BR, lowered the adhesion and cohesion strength and viscosity of the compositions. This means that these properties depend on the phase structure of the mixtures. Reference 5 studied the effect of the thermodynamic quality of a plasticizer and its composition on the physico-mechanical and rheological properties of the compositions containing EPDM, chalk, and rosin. It was found out that the introduction of ESFO and industrial oil reduced the adhesion and cohesion strength and viscosity at 120 C more significantly than in case when aromatic petroleum oil was used as the plasticizer. Such effect was also attributed to the formation of more homogeneous rubber mixtures with more miscible plasticizers. None of the quoted works try to relate the phase structure of the binding agent in compositions and their performance characteristics and do not report on the dynamic properties of the studied materials. The data about the dynamic properties of vibration damping compositions at various temperatures can be found in patents.6,7 However, this information is too fragmentary to make physically clear conclusions about the effect of the component nature and amount on these characteristics. References9-12 investigate the dynamic properties of model compositions that are, in fact, precursors of vibration damping materials also containing plasticizers. The authors of reference 9 applied dynamic analysis and DSC methods to obtain temperature dependences of the mechanical loss factor (tan δ) and to determine the glass transition points (Tg) of the compositions based on infinitely miscible BR and PIB of various molar masses. They found that (a) as the amount of low-molar-mass PIB in the mixture increased, Tg went down from −65 to −70 C and in case of the high-molar-mass PIB–from −65 to −66.4 C; (b) the introduction of high-molar-mass PIB into BR made the peak on the temperature dependence of tan δ broader and its maximum higher, whereas the introduction of low-molar-mass PIB narrowed this peak and shifted it to the low-temperature region. When studying the dynamic properties of the mixture of crosslinked BR and PIB of various compositions, the authors of reference10 found that an increase in the PIB content was accompanied by tan δ growth. Such behavior of the composition was attributed to the mobility of PIB macromolecules in the matrix consisting of crosslinked BR chains. The dynamic properties of the mixtures of LDPE with natural rubber and polypropylene (PP) with BR were studied in references 11,12. It was found11 that the temperature dependences of tan δ, regardless of the mixture composition, have two maximums at −50 C and at
