2 | EXPERIMENTAL
2.1 | Materials
The trade names, producers, and density values of the rubber, PIB, plasticizers, and fillers used in this work are listed in Table 1.
Model binding agents were prepared in a centrifugal impeller mixer for 6 h at 100 C until a constant current was established in the mixer circuit indicating that a homogeneous mixture or stable emulsion was obtained. The filled vibration damping material was made in a 5 L SH-5 L type laboratory blender with z-shaped blades at a temperature of 80 ± 5 C and rotation speed of 100–110 rpm in 30 min. The composition preparation included butyl rubber plasticization on the rollers, loading of all the components, and their mixing for 15 min. After the mixing, we took the mixture out to make 2 ± 0.1 mm thick sheets. On the one side, the material was fused with a sheet of an anti-adhesion substance, on the other it was coated with a reinforcement layer, if necessary. At the first stage of the study, we prepared model compositions containing 7.8 wt% BR, 22.2 wt% plasticizer (HRMO, I-40A, or PN-6Sh), and 70 wt% filler (chalk, talc, or kaolin) and reinforced with 50 or 90 μm thick aluminum foil. At the second stage, we prepared compositions containing bigger amounts of the polymeric component, with the environmentally hazardous I-40A and PN-6Sh oils replaced with PIB and its mixture with HRMO.
