3 | RESULTS AND DISCUSSION
3.1 | Dynamic mechanical studies
It is well-known31 that the vibration damping properties of a material are characterized by the temperature dependence of its mechanical loss factor, tan δ. The peak intensity and width describe the damping efficiency and working temperature range of the material, respectively. Figure 2 illustrates the effect of the plasticizer nature on the mechanical loss factor (tan δ) temperature dependence of the compositions containing 7.8 wt% BR. Figure 2a shows that without reinforcement the temperatures of −20, −50, and −60 C and tan δ values of 0.23, 0.20, and 0.11 decrease in the following series: PN6Sh, I-40A, HRMO, which means that the plasticizer thermodynamic affinity with BR becomes higher in the same series. Reinforcement of the materials with aluminum foil 50 μm thick does not change this order (Figure 2(b)) but shifts the tan δ maximums to the higher temperature region (to 20, −10, and −20 C) and increases the mechanical loss factor peak intensity to 0.35, 0.21, and 0.17, respectively. This results from the higher elasticity of the two-layered material, in turn, leading to an increase in the glass transition temperature and from the shear stress at the interphase boundary between the
viscoelastic composition layer and the elastic metal layer. Besides, as in references32-35 state, the higher mechanical loss factor maximum results from the lower segmental mobility in this layer. Fillers are routinely added to vibration damping formulations to reduce their cost. The effect of the filler nature on the tan δ temperature dependence is illustrated in Figure 3. For the not reinforced composition sheets (Figure 3(a)) with the same filler content (70 wt%) and particle size range ( 10–50 μm), the maximum tan δ value increases in the series: chalk, kaolin, talc. Based on the conventional ideas,31,36–40 one can assume that this stems from an increase in the filler specific surface area, Ssp, and, consequently, in the volume of the adhesive layer between the filler particles and the binding agent, other conditions being equal (no chemical interaction between the BR and filler particles and practically the same density of the latter). However, this assumption is wrong since the Ssp values increase in the series: talc, chalk, kaolin, as follows from Table 2. Thus, talc with the smallest specific surface provides the best tan δ values. This fact can be explained by the optical microscopy data in Figure 4: when chalk is replaced with talc or kaolin, the particles that are almost spherical in shape turn into scaly structures. In such a case, the friction created by scales rubbing against each other should improve the vibration damping efficiency, which agrees well with the literature data.31 Figure 3(b) demonstrates that the reinforcement of the materials with foil shifts the tan δ(T) dependence maximum to the higher temperature region by 40 C for the mixtures filled with chalk and talc and by 50 C for the mixtures filled with kaolin. The peak value increases when chalk is used, decreases for kaolin, and remains
