properties of the related systems with DSC, which is often used to estimate the level of thermodynamic affinity of polymer mixtures with various plasticizers.9,41–44 Figure 8 presents the DSC heating curves for BR, HRMO, and their pre-homogenized mixtures. The BR endotherm (curve 1) looks quite typical of elastomers and has a devitrification stage with an inflection at −62.4 C. HRMO (curve 5) exhibits a similar heat capacity jump at −83.5 C and a broad endothermic peak ranging from −70 to 0 C that describes the cumulative thermal effect produced by melting of the HRMO component eutectic mixture of an unknown composition and dissolution of the crystals of these components in this mixture. The BR/HRMO mixtures containing 80, 60, and 40 wt% of the plasticizer (curves 2–4) have a broad bimodal endotherm reflecting the melting of HRMO components and their eutectic mixtures and devitrification of these components and BR. Overlapping of the thermal effects of the above processes can lead to a deceptive conclusion that Tg of BR decreases with increasing HRMO amounts in the mixture. The industrial I-40A and aromatic petroleum PN-6Sh oils exhibit two broad but well separated endothermic peaks extending from −80 to −5 C on Figure 9(a) and from −55 to −20 C on Figure 9(b), respectively (curve 3). These peaks also reflect the thermal effects of the overlapping melting processes of oil components and their eutectic mixture, and devitrification. Curve 2 corresponding to the mixtures of I-40A with BR (Figure 9(a)) and PN-6Sh with BR (Figure 9(b)) describes the BR devitrification, in addition to the processes mentioned above for the pure plasticizers. Thus, it is impossible to estimate the level of thermodynamic affinity of mixture components and the Tg of BR
in the presence of the studied plasticizers with DSC. That is why we resorted to the laborious optical method described in the experimental part, which enabled us to construct a solubility curve of optically transparent plasticizers (HRMO and I-40A) in BR. This study took almost a year to perform because of the long duration of the diffusion processes in the mixtures and small surface area of the contact between the components. The results of the optical experiments are presented in Figure 10. The solubility curve physically represents the right branch of the liquid–liquid binodal at the phase diagram with an upper critical solution temperature. This line divides the composition–temperature field into two regions: (I) single-phase mixtures of BR with plasticizer and (II) two-phase systems, in which a plasticizer solution in BR coexists with pure plasticizer (or, in the general case, a low-concentration BR solution in the plasticizer). Since the boundary curve for the mixture containing HRMO lies in the region of lower temperatures than that of the BR mixture with I-40A, the affinity of the former plasticizer with BR is higher. It is also seen that the vibration damping compositions under study containing 20–40 wt% BR represent two-phase systems at service temperatures from −40 to 40 С. Taking into account the small diffusion rates registered in our optical experiments, it is natural to assume that the phase separation of the homogeneous mixtures obtained at elevated temperatures takes a lot of time. We used an optical microscope to obtain images of the phase structure of the BR mixture with HRMO containing 20 wt% of the polymer, cooled it to room temperature, and stored at this temperature for different amounts of time. As seen from Figures 11, 24 h after the cooling, the system still remained single-phase, and 6 months later, it
