4 | CONCLUSIONS
In this work, we have investigated how the nature of plasticizers, fillers, and reinforcing layers affects the dynamic and adhesion properties of multicomponent butyl rubber-based compositions. Based on the solubility
studies for commercial oils of different nature, we have demonstrated that at service temperatures their mixtures with BR are two-phase plasticizer emulsions in the swollen polymer. The highest viscosity has been found for the aromatic industrial PN-6Sh oil emulsion in BR with the lowest swelling degree of the polymeric component. Filled compositions based on this system reveal the best vibration damping properties but can be ecologically dangerous. We have proposed a novel formulation of the binding agent containing the mixture of BR polymer with polyisobutylene as modifying agent and highly-refined mineral oil as plasticizer. It has been established that introduction of PIB and HRMO considerably increases the mixture viscosity and its performance properties. The thermodynamic parameters of the viscous flow activation process have been calculated to qualitatively explain this effect. The chalk-filled and aluminum foil-reinforced compositions based on the BR/PIB/HRMO mixture are environmentally safe and attractive in terms of industrial applications. They meet main requirements for effective vibration damping materials, providing the cohesion strength of 3.5–5.0 N cm−1, penetration of 4.5–6.0 mm, and mechanical loss factor, tan δ > 0.25. The temperature range of their usage can be regulated by variation of the HRMO content.
